notes.note: Enrollment limited to: History graduate students.

As part of the new ¿history of capitalism¿ movement, this graduate seminar will map out a complex understanding of working class experience, politics, and identity in the United States as they were shaped by both culture and economic structure. In so doing, we will triangulate our subject through three fields of history¿socio-cultural, economic, and labor¿in order to gain a fuller understanding of United States history. Framed within the broadest ideas in the history of capitalism, we will study both free and unfree labor regimes, while focusing on problems such as class formation, race, gender, the state, business, and ideology. Although we will take United States labor and working-class history as our main reference point (historiographically, economically, politically), the seminar will make sustained forays into, and connections with, the working-class histories of other nations. We will read more than one monograph per week, submit six one-page reviews, and write two long papers during the semester.
